entry.title: Reland "Notify OffscreenCanvas of lost context after a GPU crash"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit ac3db87b1ba40f01151c1fdbc45959f362e0bda8



The call to NotifyGpuContextLost is now done from the offscreen

rendering context. The frame dispatcher is not touched until the

TryRestore event is triggered (also from the offscreen rendering

context) and it can be rebuilt. I could not reproduce the ASAN issue

locally, but it is passing the bots referenced in bug 1491175.



Original change's description:

> Notify OffscreenCanvas of lost context after a GPU crash

>

> In order for an OffscreenCanvas to recover from a lost context caused by

> a GPU crash, it has to be notified of it via NotifyGpuContextLost. This

> change adds a check before an existing ResourceProvider is returned from

> OffscreenCanvas, in order to call NotifyGpuContextLost if the GPU was

> being used and its context has been lost.

>

> A test has been added to check that the context is restored correctly

> when issuing new draw calls after the GPU crash.

>

entry.title: Handle DoDeferredCloseWindowSoon on a swapped out WebViewImpl
entry.content:
With RenderDocument, cross-document same-site navigations will use

new LocalFrames that will use a new WebView in case of main frames.

After committing the new LocalFrame in the new WebView, the old

WebView's LocalFrame will be detached, so it won't have any valid

local_main_frame_host_remote_ or remote_main_frame_host_remote_.



This caused crashes in some test that calls window.close() on the

old document just before it gets unloaded, causing the close task

to run after the LocalFrame gets detached, and

DoDeferredCloseWindowSoon() tried to access the non-existent

remote_main_frame_host_remote_.



This CL fixes the crash by introducing CloseTaskHandler, which

keeps track of the "current" Page, ensuring that the close task

will run on the new a non-detached WebView in the case mentioned

above.



Bug: 936696

entry.title: Move RuleData Bloom filter hashes into separate storage.
entry.content:
This saves a bit of RAM and gives us more flexibility (e.g. to support

more than four Bloom hashes per element, or to have some other

variable-length storage). It also makes RuleData smaller, fitting better

into cache, but the win is small and is mostly offset by the fact

the hashes are now no longer colocated with the RuleData and thus

may need an extra cache miss. This is especially true for tests

where selectors have a lot of descendant selectors; e.g., see

style recalc on the Sports test below.



Style perftest (LTO but no PGO, Zen 2):



Initial style (µs) Before After Perf 95% CI (BCa)

=================== ========= ========= ======= =================

ECommerce 8943 8909 +0.4% [ +0.1%, +0.6%]

Encyclopedia 86822 87172 -0.4% [ -0.8%, +0.6%]

Extension 117214 117360 -0.1% [ -0.4%, +0.3%]

News 37891 37947 -0.1% [ -0.4%, +0.1%]

Search 10877 10827 +0.5% [ -0.1%, +0.7%]

Social1 22931 22477 +2.0% [ +1.9%, +2.2%]

Social2 14851 14801 +0.3% [ +0.1%, +0.7%]

Sports 45078 44921 +0.3% [ +0.1%, +0.6%]

Video 32679 32534 +0.4% [ +0.2%, +0.6%]

Geometric mean +0.4% [ +0.3%, +0.5%]



Recalc style (µs) Before After Perf 95% CI (BCa)

=================== ========= ========= ======= =================

ECommerce 9748 9781 -0.3% [ -0.8%, +0.2%]

Encyclopedia 67205 67574 -0.5% [ -1.2%, +0.5%]

Extension 109405 109388 +0.0% [ -0.4%, +0.9%]

News 33233 33516 -0.8% [ -1.2%, +0.1%]

Search 5537 5570 -0.6% [ -1.1%, -0.1%]

Social1 15090 14940 +1.0% [ +0.1%, +1.4%]

Social2 11291 11257 +0.3% [ +0.0%, +0.6%]

Sports 23422 24259 -3.5% [ -3.7%, -3.1%]

Video 21037 21039 -0.0% [ -0.4%, +1.0%]

Geometric mean -0.5% [ -0.7%, -0.2%]



We could offset the performance issue somewhat by being more careful

about the order we keep the Bloom filter hash vector in (RuleDatas

from the same bucket could have hashes put next to each other),

but this adds some extra complexity and we haven't gone down that route.

Similarly, we could now more easily store only the 24 bits we need for

each hash, but haven't done so. Prototypes indicate that this would gain

back 1–2% on the Sports test.



RAM usage for Bloom hashes (without malloc overhead, just counting how

much smaller RuleData becomes and how much more we stick into the

vector):



ECommerce 23 kB → 10 kB ( -13 kB)

Encyclopedia 84 kB → 41 kB ( -43 kB)

Extension 30 kB → 9 kB ( -23 kB)

News 86 kB → 58 kB ( -30 kB)

Search 51 kB → 20 kB ( -31 kB)

Social1 166 kB → 44 kB (-122 kB)

Social2 20 kB → 7 kB ( -13 kB)

Sports 382 kB → 203 kB (-179 kB)

Video 200 kB → 83 kB (-117 kB)



In theory, we would use more RAM if almost every RuleData had four or

more descendant selectors (we are at break-even at 3), but in practice,

this never happens.

entry.content:

password and it was cleared. Because of that, the call to the function

DidClearGenerationSuggestion never happens, meaning that password

confirmation field is never cleared.

prefix of b). In this case, the distance should be i+1, the length of

the prefix of a.

entry.title: Add event.addRoutes() to InstallEvent
entry.content:
Based on the recent discussion on the Github issue [1], we introduce

`addRoutes()` to InstallEvent, which is another way to register routing

info.



Summary:

1.Unlike `registerRouter()`, `addRoutes()` can be called multiple times.

2.`registerRouter()` remains as it is, at least until OT end date.

3.`addRoutes()` and `registerRouter()` are exclusive. Raises exceptions

once both methods are called.

entry.title: media/gpu/v4l2: Teach V4L2StatefulVD to split H.264 NALUs into frames
entry.content:
It turns out that Hana doesn't like to be fed a PPS NALU together with

the first subsequent non-/IDR frame (and many a test vector in the H.264

conformance tests do something like this). Instead, Hana needs to be

fed one full frame at a time -- this is different from Trogdor, whose

only requirement is that whatever is enqueued is not a partial frame.



This CL adds code to the H264FrameReassembler methods to handle this

situation: FindH264FrameBoundaries() is taught to return the location

of the frame boundary (instead of a full frame found yes/no), and

Process() is taught to split frames when they contain more than one

full frame, and to return a vector of DecoderBuffers ready to

enqueue (and their corresponding DecodeCBs).



With this V4L2StatefulVD is closer to parity with the legacy ToT when

it comes to MD5 ChromeStackDecoderVerification for H.264; there's

still some oddities (e.g. CAPCM1_Sand_E.h264 CAPCMNL1_Sand_E.h264

which are left for a later CL to avoid cluttering this one too much).

entry.title: siso: no need to write tsconfig.json or tsconfig.definitions.json
entry.content:
These files are not appeared in build graph.

By writing it is stored in hashfs, but it won't be written to

disk since it is not in output.

In next build, it detects the file does not exist on disk,

so hashfs does not clean, so need to run schedule but

all steps are up-to-date and finish with "ninja: no work to do".



Without writing these files, build succeeded

and the next build can finish quickly with

"Everything is up-to-date"
